ENTRY       EC 2.4.1.241                Enzyme
NAME        digalactosyldiacylglycerol synthase;
            DGD1;
            DGD2;
            DGDG synthase (ambiguous);
            UDP-galactose-dependent DGDG synthase;
            UDP-galactose-dependent digalactosyldiacylglycerol synthase;
            UDP-galactose:MGDG galactosyltransferase;
            UDP-galactose:3-(beta-D-galactosyl)-1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 6-alpha-galactosyltransferase
CLASS       Transferases;
            Glycosyltransferases;
            Hexosyltransferases
SYSNAME     UDP-alpha-D-galactose:1,2-diacyl-3-O-(beta-D-galactosyl)-sn-glycerol 6-alpha-galactosyltransferase
REACTION    UDP-alpha-D-galactose + 1,2-diacyl-3-O-(beta-D-galactosyl)-sn-glycerol = UDP + 1,2-diacyl-3-O-[alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-galactosyl]-sn-glycerol [RN:R04469]
ALL_REAC    R04469
SUBSTRATE   UDP-alpha-D-galactose [CPD:C00052];
            1,2-diacyl-3-O-(beta-D-galactosyl)-sn-glycerol
PRODUCT     UDP [CPD:C00015];
            1,2-diacyl-3-O-[alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-galactosyl]-sn-glycerol
COMMENT     Requires Mg2+. Diacylglycerol cannot serve as an acceptor molecule for galactosylation as in the reaction catalysed by EC 2.4.1.46, monogalactosyldiacylglyerol synthase. When phosphate is limiting, phospholipids in plant membranes are reduced but these are replaced, at least in part, by the glycolipids digalactosyldiacylglycerol (DGDG) and sulfoquinovosyldiacylglycerol [3]. While both DGD1 and DGD2 are increased under phosphate-limiting conditions, DGD2 does not contribute significantly under optimal growth conditions. DGD2 is responsible for the synthesis of DGDG molecular species that are rich in C16 fatty acids at sn-1 of diacylglycerol whereas DGD1 leads to molecular species rich in C18 fatty acids [3]. The enzyme has been localized to the outer side of chloroplast envelope membranes.
